    "Thermonuclear reactionsLocal thermodynamic equilibrium implies that at temperatures above neutron decoupling, a nuclear species i of atomic number Z i, mass number A i, spin s i, and binding energy B i follows a Boltzmann distribution with internal degrees of freedom: g i = 2s i +1; mass:m i = Z i m p +(A i -Z i)m n -B i; and chemical potential: μ i = Z i μ p + (A i -Z i)μ n.In terms of the yield Y i ≡ n i /n B, this equilibrium distribution reads:Y i T γ MeV = g i 2 (3A i -5)/2 Y Z i p Y A i -Z i n exp B i T γ × ζ(3) η B √ π A i -1 m i T A i -1 γ m Z i p m A i -Z i n 3/2, (16)where we made use of:n B /η B = 3 ζ(3) T 3 γ /(2π 2).",
